<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much ventilation does my house need?", answer: "ASHRAE 62.2-2022 requires Q_total = 0.03 × floor area (sq ft) + 7.5 × (bedrooms + 1) CFM of outdoor air. A 2,000 sq ft, 3-bedroom house needs 0.03 × 2000 + 7.5 × 4 = 60 + 30 = 90 CFM total. This can come from a mix of mechanical ventilation and infiltration." },
  { question: "What is the difference between an HRV and an ERV?", answer: "Both are whole-house mechanical ventilation units that exchange stale indoor air for fresh outdoor air while recovering energy. An HRV (Heat Recovery Ventilator) transfers only sensible heat. An ERV (Energy Recovery Ventilator) transfers both heat and moisture. Use an ERV in humid climates where you want to keep some humidity out in summer and retain some humidity in winter. HRVs are common in dry cold climates like northern Canada." },
  { question: "What is an infiltration credit?", answer: "ASHRAE 62.2 allows you to subtract unintentional infiltration from the required mechanical ventilation rate — but only up to a limit and only if you have a measured blower door test. A leaky house already brings in some outdoor air through envelope leaks, so less fans are needed. Typical credit: 5 ACH50 in a 1500 sq ft house reduces required mechanical CFM by about 15 CFM." },
  { question: "Does the kitchen range hood count toward ventilation?", answer: "Only if it vents to outside and operates continuously. Most range hoods are intermittent (used only while cooking) and don't count toward the whole-house rate. ASHRAE 62.2 requires separate 100 CFM kitchen exhaust and 50 CFM bathroom exhaust in addition to the whole-house rate." },
  { question: "What if I live in a new tight house?", answer: "Modern code-compliant houses (especially passive house / zero-energy) are so tight that they need mechanical ventilation to meet ASHRAE 62.2 — natural infiltration alone cannot provide enough fresh air. An ERV running continuously at 60-120 CFM is typical. The calculator shows how much mechanical CFM you need if you enter an ACH50 from a blower door test." }
]) %>

